<subSubSection id="242DFD1D1AE8B9E9DC66E5EF48859DE8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="AD1DF746181C623B213C99A2230A10AA" pageNumber="45">
The combination of a small body size and greatly enlarged fin spines in 
<taxonomicName id="B52B4969733E02CBC6D9B3DB7E30D678" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:9D2F348F-572B-42AF-BB60-8EC94D3534F9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Pseudolaguvia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Pseudolaguvia muricata Ng 2005" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="muricata">P. muricata</taxonomicName>
is seldom seen in the Siluriformes, being only known in the members of the Neotropical Doradidae and the Erethistidae. Within the Erethistidae, it is known to occur in one other erethistid, 
<taxonomicName id="8E165844F3956EA961A08DA3484F71EA" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:62BD88DA-7888-4A20-AE92-B82DB0C5AEF8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Hara" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hara jerdoni Day 1870:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jerdoni">Hara jerdoni</taxonomicName>
. Again, the underlying reason for this unusual morphology is unclear. At least two hypotheses can be postulated for this: 1) the spines are an antipredator defense mechanism and 2) the spines may be useful in helping the fish maintain station in a swift-flowing environment. Although both hypotheses require rigorous testing beyond the scope of this study, they are seemingly supported by the (personal) observation that individuals of 
<taxonomicName id="F788E138B459D009C1C41EAAB0AEB8D0" LSID-ZBK="urn:lsid:zoobank.org:act:62BD88DA-7888-4A20-AE92-B82DB0C5AEF8" class="Actinopterygii" family="Erethistidae" genus="Hara" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-ZBK="Hara jerdoni Day 1870:39" order="Siluriformes" pageNumber="45" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="jerdoni">Hara jerdoni</taxonomicName>
frequently remain at rest with the fin spines partially or fully erect amongst submerged vegetation.
</paragraph>
